          <h3>Name</h3>
          <p>
            Choosing a name is not required but if you do choose a name,
            you can earn points for completing units of work.
            <!-- You can check
            if a name is already in use by clicking "Validate Name" above. -->
          </p>

          <h3>Team #</h3>
          <p>If you have joined a team you should enter your team number
            above.  This will allow the points you earn to be added to your
            team's total.  For more information about teams and points see
            the <a href="http://folding.stanford.edu/English/Stats">Stats
              Page</a>.</p>

          <h3>Passkey</h3>
          <p>Passkeys are used to add an extra level of security for those
            competing for points.  Getting a passkey will also allow you
            to earn bonus points for completing work early.  For more
            information or to get a passkey use the following links:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="http://folding.stanford.edu/English/FAQ-passkey"
                   >Passkey - Frequently Asked Questions</a></li>
            <li>
              <a href="http://fah-web.stanford.edu/cgi-bin/getpasskey.py"
                 >Get a Passkey</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div id="help">
          <div id="what_is_fah">
            <div class="title">What is Folding@home?</div>
            <img alt="Folding@home logo"
               src="http://folding.stanford.edu/pub/images/FAHLogo-128.png"/>
            <p>
              Simply by running this software you are helping scientists
              study Alzheimer's, Huntington's, and many cancers.
            </p>
            <p>
              You are also participating in the world's most powerful
              distributed super-computer.
            </p>
            <p>
              People like you, all over the globe, are putting
              their unused computer time to good use.
            </p>
            <p>
              Scientists at Stanford University and around the world utilize
              your donated computer time to better understand and develop
              cures for some of humanity's worst diseases.
            </p>
            <p>
              For more information see the
              <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Folding@home"
                 >Folding@home Wikipedia page</a>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div id="what_are_proteins">
            <div class="title">What are proteins?</div>
            <img class="right" alt="Protein folding"
                 src="http://folding.stanford.edu/pub/images/protein-folding.png"/>
            <p>
              Proteins are biology's workhorses -- its "nanomachines."
              Proteins help your body break down food into energy, regulate
              your moods, and fight disease.
            </p>

            <p>
              For more information see the
              <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protein"
                 >Protein Wikipedia page</a>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div id="what_is_folding">
            <div class="title">What is protein folding?</div>
            <p>
              Before proteins can carry out these important functions, they
              assemble themselves, or "fold."  While protein folding is
              critical and fundamental to virtually all of biology, much of
              the process remains a mystery.
            </p>

            <p>For more information see our
              <a href='http://folding.stanford.edu/English/Science'>Science
                page</a> and the
              <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protein_folding"
                 >Protein Folding Wikipedia page</a>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div id="why_it_matters_next">
            <div class="title">Why does protein folding matter?</div>
            <img alt="Protein misfolding"
                 src="http://folding.stanford.edu/pub/images/misfolding.png"/>
            <p>
              When proteins do not fold correctly, also known as misfolding,
              there can be serious health consequences, including many well
              known diseases, such as Alzheimer's, Mad Cow (BSE), CJD, ALS,
              Huntington's, Parkinson's disease, and many cancers.
            </p>

            <p>
              If we better understand protein misfolding we can design drugs
              and therapies to combat these illnesses.
            </p>

            <p>
              For more information see our
              <a href="http://folding.stanford.edu/English/FAQ-Diseases"
                 >Folding@home disease FAQ</a>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div id="affect_of_fah">
            <div class="title">How will it affect my computer?</div>
            <p>
              Once installed, the Folding@home software runs behind the scenes
              taking advantage of otherwise unused computing time.  Mostly
              likely you will hardly even notice it.
            </p>
            <p>
              We have yet to receive any reports of Folding@home physically
              damaging anyone's computer.  On rare occasions, and especially
              with older laptops, some users have reported video lag,
              excessive heat or fan noise.  If any of these symptoms occur on
              your computer simply move the folding power slider down a notch
              or two.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div id='how_to_help'>
            <div class="title">How can I help more?</div>
            <img alt="Folding@home logo"
               src="http://folding.stanford.edu/pub/images/FAHLogo-128.png"/>
            <p>
              One of the best ways to help Folding@home is by recruiting your
              friends and family.
            </p>
            <p>
              You can even start your own team and compete for points.  The
              more points you and your team earn the closer we come to
              understanding and solving some of mankind's worst diseases.
            </p>

            <p>
              If you would like to make a donation o our non-profit
              organization please visit the
              <a href="http://folding.stanford.edu/English/Donate">Donations
                page</a>.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div id="more_help">
            <div class="title question">Where can I get more help?</div>
            <div class="answer">
              <ul>
                <li>The <a href="http://folding.stanford.edu/English/FAQ"
                           >Folding@home Frequently Asked Questions page</a>
                  answers many common questions.</li>
                <li>The <a href="http://foldingforum.org/">Folding Forum</a>
                  has a very active community of expert folders who would be
                  glad to help you with any problems you might have.  It is
                  also a great place to get more involved.
                </li>
                <li>On the
                  <a href="https://fah-web.stanford.edu/projects/FAHClient/"
                     >Client Development Project page</a> you can find
                  technical information about the software, report bugs and
                  learn about the <a href="https://fah-web.stanford.edu/projects/FAHClient/wiki/ClientRemoteInterface">3rd-party
                    development API</a>.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

